Text.Value: All right - I'll see what I can do.
Rejoice, sisters, for Umberlee has blessed her humble daughter with a pure death!
Umberlee smiles on us all! Thank you for enacting her blessed vengeance - may the tides crush his bones to sand.

EditorData.NodeContext: Exultant on the first sentence, then grateful (and vicious after the -)

Text.Value: Holli, one of Umberlee's beloved waveservants.
This 'precious gift' isn't drowning, is it?
An act of divine mercy!
I've brought gold. ([GEN_CheckMagicPocketGold_6057ad05-9492-4630-9f0a-be548b134c54])
We will find its master and send him struggling into the Bitch Queen's embrace!
An intercession to another of the First Circle? The Depthqueen will be most pleased.
The other gods do not look kindly on the Bitch Queen - but she looks kindly upon your prayers, priest.
*You're reminded of the Banite's submersible. Could they be connected?*
The beast struck Holli while she was swimming in Grey Harbour. She was found by some fishermen.
Yes! Then you know as well as Umberlee that blood must soon be shed.

EditorData.NodeContext: Excited by the prospect of revenge

Text.Value: I've already made a tribute.
Leave.
We are celebrating an act of divine mercy!
Umberlee's mercy saved her from a slow, sinking death in the beast's shadow!
A layperson's prayers - crude but earnest.
Where can I find the beast's master?
Salt kiss your brow! We await your return - and the beastmaster's demise.

EditorData.NodeContext: Ecstatic; very glad the player is going to help

Text.Value: The 'beast's master' has already left the city - I found his resignation letter. Your waters are safe.
Did this person drown?
How did Umberlee 'spare her an ignoble death'?
A fine offering always appreciated in the eyes of the Wavemother.

EditorData.NodeContext: Pleased by the offering of gold

Text.Value: I wish her soul the stillness of a calmed ocean.
A wretched metal monstrosity hewn by hubris.
Who's the deceased?
Blessed Umberlee saw fit to spare her an ignoble death, but her passing was not as the Wavemother intended.
Holli was swimming in Grey Harbour - as we all do. The beast struck her and she lost consciousness - Umberlee eased her passing.
I have yet to meet a beast I couldn't slay. If you need a hunter, you've found one.
I think I know the master of the 'poisonous beast'. I'll see what I can do.
The beastmaster is dead.
She would have suffered a terrible, agonising death had Umberlee not bestowed upon her the mercy of drowning.

EditorData.NodeContext: Truly, fanatically believes the drowning was a mercy

Text.Value: Your tribute is well received. Breathe deep as she permits.

EditorData.NodeContext: Pleased by the player's offering to Umberlee

Text.Value: I'm good at slaying beasts - maybe I could help you.
Yes! Rage and rebel against the beast and its master! A tribute most fitting.
Where can I find this beastmaster again?
It was a beast who took her life - an unnatural one whose very existence is an affront to Umberlee.
The Queen of the Depths is generous to those who serve her - and her favour is far less deadly than her wrath.

EditorData.NodeContext: Keen for the player to help her; confident in Umberlee's bounty

Text.Value: Then come back when you have. The Wavemother is rarely patient.
Remind me what the beast did to your waveservant.
We haven't found its lair as yet - perhaps you can find where the beast takes its slumber and skewer it before it wakes.

EditorData.NodeContext: Intense; wants the beast's master gone

Text.Value: A rusting pollutant that bleeds black blood into Umberlee's pristine waters.

*You're reminded of the man you met beneath the Grey Harbour - and the submersible he
commanded.*
How dare this beast sully the safety of Grey Harbour!
May the Wavemother grant you her favour - or at least, spare you her wrath.
ROAR.
Yes, thank the Wavemother!
Her lips blue with her kiss, her lungs full of her quenching word!
I've brought my weapon to help avenge her death.
Pft, that privilege is not yours to earn.

EditorData.NodeContext: Dismissive; the player is not worthy of such a fate in her eyes

Text.Value: I haven't brought any tribute, actually.
As promised. The Wavemother rewards those who submit to her will.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: Receive reward for completing the quest
EditorData.NodeContext: Reverently bestowing a reward on the deserving player

Text.Value: I'm not getting involved in this.
Is it done? Have you slain the beastmaster?

EditorData.NodeContext: Enthusiastically hopeful about the beastmaster's death

Text.Value: Then you'd better have a good reason for approaching so brazenly.

EditorData.NodeContext: Slightly irritated by the player's lack of an offering

Text.Value: As still as the water in her halted lungs! A most fitting tribute, received with gratitude.

EditorData.NodeContext: first sentence agreeing with player, almost congratulatory (to another zealot who's died a noble death)

Text.Value: The 'beast's master' has been dealt with. You're welcome.
Not a sweet sleep like Holli's, but a suffocating flood of fruitless gasps and bursting flesh!

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Camera on corpse of the dead waveservant on an altar; back onto Allandra after

Text.Value: Nice corpse. What are we celebrating?
You have done the Bitch Queen's house a great deed - I pray that when you die, your lungs are blessed with her salted kisses.
I suspect I know the origins of this 'beast'. I'll see what I can do.

EditorData.logicalname: knows about iron throne but not bastmaster

Text.Value: The 'beast's master' left Baldur's Gate - I found his resignation letter. Your waters are safe.
May the seas be as kind as you deserve.

EditorData.NodeContext: A warm - if slightly threatening-sounding - farewell

Text.Value: Changeable as the sea - have you decided to help after all?
There is always time for the tides - pray you never get caught in them.
Not yet.
Then I hope you never have need of the sea's benevolence.
This is one of the more upbeat funerals I've attended.
Find the master of this poisonous beast and slay him - then one of her most precious gifts shall be yours.

EditorData.NodeContext: Keen for the player to help her; confident in Umberlee's bounty

Text.Value: Sorry, I don't have time for this.
I've brought a prayer.
I'll find the beastmaster.
You! Supplicant! What tribute do you bring to honour the Wavemother's fallen daughter?
I will ensure the Weavemistress watches over her soul.
I will pray for her in the Dwarffather's name.
I will ask the Forest Queen to find a safe path for her soul.
The Queen of the Dark Seldarine will see her soul safely to the afterlife.
My prayers will grant her the Morninglord's shining light.
I will ask for Laduguer's aid in her passing.
The Lord of the Dead will smooth her soul's passage - I will ensure it.
She will suffer no more in death - the Rack-Broken Lord will ensure that.
I will entreat Helm to keep her in his watchful gaze.
I will pray that Gruumsh grants her vengeance eternal.
I will pray that Garl Glittergold protects her soul in death.
I will pray that Eilistraee guides her final dance.
I will pray to the Elffather for her.
I will pray that the Platinum Dragon's shining light guides her spirit.
I will pray that her soul holds Oghma's wisdom in death.
A simple prayer - that the Silver Lady's light guides her soul.
I will ask the Lady of Loss to guide her into the night eternal.
I pray she rests in the stormy waves of Talos' embrace.
It sounds like she died in battle - I will pray for Tempus to guide her soul.
Tiamat's unholy flame - may its light guide her in death.
Tymora's luck - may your fallen carry it into the afterlife.
Lord Tyr will intercede for your dead.
Your pathetic dead will bask in the glory of Vlaakith's prayer.
An intercession from the Lady of Plenty.
I will pray to my god for her salvation.

Synopsis:
Player talks to Allandra Grey, the Flood Tide (High Priestes) that serves the Water Queen. 
She's somewhat cold and strict. Talking to her will give some information about the funeral that is happening in the temple, and eventually she gives out the quest Waveservant's Demise, where player should investigate the murder of her waveservant.
